TO Oluwaseun Ogunwale
======================

The first step in analyzing the IMU orientation would be to estimate the device's orientation using an Attitude and Heading Reference System (AHRS) that combines the accelerometer and gyroscope readings. This will give us quaternion values representing the rotation of the sensor with respect to the initial reference frame.
After obtaining the quaternions, we can convert them into Euler angles if necessary for better interpretation of the orientation.
Here's how I plan to proceed:

```python
imu_oriented = imuOrientation(acc) # Estimate orientation as quaternons using AHSR fusion
# Convert quaternations to Euler Angles if required
roll, pitch, yaw = eulerAnglesFromQuat(imuOriented)
``
Once we have the Euler angle values, we should get a good idea about the approximate orientation of device based on its x, y, z components. The combination of these three angles gives us information regarding the tilt and orientation of our device.
Based on this information, we may be able to deduce where the user is wearing their device. For example, if the pitch value indicates a large forward lean, it could suggest that the device is worn around the waist or chest area while walking. Similarly, if there is significant variation in the roll angle, it might indicate that the user has rotated their upper body during the walk.
Finally, once we have gathered sufficient evidence through various analyses, we will conclude whether the device seems to be worn on the torso or elsewhere.
